Name: n-Pentacosane
Description: Pentacosane is an alkane consisting of an unbranched chain of 25 carbon atoms. It has a role as a semiochemical and a plant metabolite.

fish_seafood_concentrations.References: (1) Al-Hassan JM et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 65: 646-53 (2000) (2) Al-Hassan JM et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 66: 646-52 (2001)
fish_seafood_concentrations.Value: Barnacle samples collected from five locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of pentacosane ranging from not detected to 970 ng/g(1). Catfish samples collected from seven locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of octadecane ranging from not detected to 126 ng/g(2).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Hori T et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 83: 455-461 (2009)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SEDIMENTS: Pentacosane was detected in sediment samples from 14 sites along the Shinano River in Japan, from Nov 2005 to April 2006, at concentrations ranging from 0.8 to 14 ng/g dry weight(1).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Rushdi AI et al; Arch Environ Contam Toxicol 49: 457-470 (2005)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SOIL: During winter 2002 soil and sand samples, from six locations in the Riyadh metropolitan area of Saudi Arabia, were examined for extractable organic matter; pentacosane was detected at relative concentrations between 0.01 to 1.20% (of total extractable organic matter) at all six locations(1).
